@realmoney Calls for Rate Cuts Today Lack a Sense of History * Rates are already negative in real terms * Rather than learn from history we seem destined to make the same monetary mistakes again Calls for a rate cut will likely intensify over the next few days. But monetary

stimulation, after a decade of growth and spectacular market gains, is not the answer - we just have to look at the BOJ and ECB as two perfect examples of how not to conduct monetary policy. Ever lower rates cause "mischief" and the misallocation of resources which hurts our

economy further down the road. Low rates prevent natural price discovery (in our stock market), perpetuate "zombie companies" and are not always the right policy solution - though they "seem" to be, always. If it was as easy as cutting rates, yields would forever be low, with

no adverse economic ramifications. Economies have to be "flushed" at times, as blunt and cold as that sounds. That flushing prevents such events as The Great Recession of 2007-09. Calls for rate cuts today lack a sense of history. Furthermore, these calls suggest current

economic statistics are inaccurate or something else is awry. Either way the calls are dumb as rates are. @jimcramer @tomkeene @squawkcnbc @cnbcfastmoney @michaelsantoli @andrewrsorkin @beckyquick @Sarge986 @SullyCNBC
